**Overview:**

Starting on Yoodli felt like entering a polished, “product-first” experience that’s designed to get you into a practice session as fast as possible. The welcome page is clearly a marketing front door: it explains the value (interactive AI roleplays), shows strong calls-to-action (start roleplaying / sign in), and builds trust with visible compliance messaging and an always-available support chat widget. From there, the flow quickly shifts from selling the idea to using it, which makes the platform feel straightforward even on a first visit.​

After signing in, the onboarding question (“what do you want to use this for?”) is a simple but important step, because it personalizes what you see next and narrows the platform to a specific goal. Choosing “interview preparation” routes you into an Interview Practice workspace that looks and behaves like a real web app, with a left sidebar for navigation and a central area for setting up the session. The setup is structured: you choose a roleplay type (behavioral/technical or create your own), pick an interviewer persona, and optionally specify the role and company—details that make the simulation feel more realistic and targeted.​

The strongest part of the experience is how it exposes the “logic” of the practice before you begin: it shows a rubric (like active listening and STAR method) and offers a Practice Questions tab where you can edit or add questions. That makes the session feel less random and more like training with a defined standard, not just chatting with an AI. Finally, once you hit the start stage, the interface becomes a live interview session screen with a timer and call-style controls, making it clear the interaction is intended to be real-time and performance-based.​

For building a university version, a key insight is that Yoodli’s value isn’t only “AI responses,” but the product layers around the model: templates, onboarding intent selection, rubric-based evaluation, editable question banks, and a real-time session experience that implies audio capture, turn-taking, and post-session feedback generation.

Tips for your documentation and coding: capture how each step changes what the AI should do (intent → scenario template → question list → evaluation rubric) and note where user inputs should be persisted so sessions can feel consistent over time. Also, document permission prompts and what’s recorded (audio/transcripts), because the experience strongly suggests recording and analytics, and students will care about privacy and access controls.
